Whispers &amp; Street Talk#Bridgeport is a city of a thousand conversations happening at once. Not all of them are meant to be heard. These are fragments — caught across a tavern table, overheard on a dock, picked up in passing on Queensway. Make of them what you will.
&ldquo;Paved it twice in eight months. Ask anyone who works Queensway. First crew said the ground wasn&rsquo;t settling right underneath. Second crew just did the job and kept their mouths shut.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Lenn went down the lower access near Ferwick Street. Was gone two days longer than the job called for. Won&rsquo;t say where he was the extra time. Won&rsquo;t say much of anything, really.&rdquo;
&ldquo;The rats near Coppergate have stopped going near the old drainage channel. All of them. Just — stopped. Three weeks now.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Someone&rsquo;s been patching the old sewer infrastructure under the Racket. Good work, too. No work orders filed. Nobody&rsquo;s claimed it.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Party took a contract out of the Guild — harbor district, infrastructure job. Came back inside a week, handed in their token, and left the city. No report filed. Nobody&rsquo;s talking about why.&rdquo;
&ldquo;She cancelled two Council sessions. Seraphina Velcross. Scheduling conflicts, they said. Ask anyone who&rsquo;s worked with her for more than a year if she cancels Council sessions.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Ship out of Dalraven came in last week. Crew said weather. You look at that hull damage and you tell me that&rsquo;s weather.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Old Marek&rsquo;s been farming that same stretch south of the city for thirty years. Says the winter was wrong. Not cold enough in the low fields, too cold on the rises. Says the ground feels different. Won&rsquo;t say how.&rdquo;
More will surface as the party moves through the city and keeps their ears open.
